#Text=It depends on the Web browser you are using for specifics , but for each major Web browser there are tools you can install ( besides DuckDuckGo extensions ) to protect you in various scenarios .
#Text=Some of those that are available in multiple browsers are Ghostery , DoNotTrackMe , and HTTPS Everywhere .
#Text=Those help protect you while not really changing your browsing experience .
#Text=Other tools do more , but do impact your browsing experience , like Tor and NoScript .
#Text=What is your opinion of ad block tools such as AdBlockPlus and NoScript that ideally aim to block third-party js ?
#Text=I think they are effective at doing what they set out to do , and that is great if you are a consumer who wants that experience .
#Text=However , they are not for everyone because they do degrade browsing ability , especially NoScript .
#Text=Do you think that DoNotTarget option should exist ( if consistendly adhered to ) ?
#Text=Absolutely .
#Text=My main problem with the DoNotTrack setting right now is it is misleading .
#Text=If you use a major Web browser , you have this Do Not Track setting within it , but it really does next to nothing .
#Text=It is a false sense of security .
#Text=What do you see the ideal behaviour of companies when it comes to making a user 's profile ?
#Text=Would you like to ideally prohibit such activity entirely using legislative regulations in the long run ?
#Text=Yes , I think an analogy to the Do Not Call list is apt .
#Text=Applying that analogy , if you were on a Do Not Track list then companies should n't track you unless you explicitly ask them to , e.g. by logging in and consenting to Terms of Service .
#Text=That will only happen via legislative means , however .
#Text=Opera
#Text=Flage Bratsberg , Product Counsel , Opera Software
#Text=ASA
#Text=Wikinews also interviewed Haakon Flage Bratsberg , Product Counsel from Opera Software , the corporation behind Opera web browser .
#Text=Have you heard of " Do Not Track " feature support in modern browsers ?
#Text=What do you think about it ?
#Text=Opera browser for desktop computers has built in support for Do Not Track since version 12 , and Opera Software participates in the W3C Tracking Protection Working Group .
#Text=Given that not all companies respect this setting , do you feel its name misleading ?
#Text=Do you think it could better be named " Do Not Target " instead ?
#Text=This is our major concern about the DNT functionality : Users can be given a false sense of security .
#Text=Do you think that all websites should respect DNT users ' preferences in the long run ?
#Text=In general we think websites should comply with web standards , including the current proposal for DNT .
#Text=Would you ideally see the respect for DNT users ' preferences legally enforced ?
